		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Why Possession Removal is a Good Thing!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.33)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 17, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
     Alright, almost everyone knows that condition discard is a good thing, right? From Albert Dreary to Company of Archers, from Sleep Caradhras to Fortress Never Fallen. We may even see some Deep in Thought action with the new Gandalf cards. There may have been a few I’ve not mentioned, but the point isn’t to mention all the condition discard. It’s to illustrate that, whenever possible, people include condition discard to aid their deck and give protection against those nasty shadow conditions. <br />
<br />
However, I have yet to see any active possession removal. Starting with the release of BOHD, that may change. Right now, though, it still doesn’t hurt to add it in. <br />
<br />
First, here are the possession discard cards that I know of.<br />
<br />
Something Draws Near<br />
Event<br />
Manuever: Exert an elf to discard an [Isengard] possession or <br />
[Isengard] artifact.<br />
Cost: 0<br />
<br />
Might come in handy in an elf deck, but is probably too limited to be useful. Isengard isn’t heavy on possession, so let’s move on to the next.<br />
<br />
Roll of Thunder<br />
Event<br />
Fellowship or Manuever: Spot Gandalf to discard a shadow <br />
possession or artifact.<br />
Cost: 3<br />
<br />
Nice. It requires no exertion and there’s no limit to what culture it has to be. <br />
Additionally, it can discard artifacts, not that they are very common, but it could help. This works best with Gandalf the White Wizard and other Gandalf spells. It provides 3 twilight that could be used to help or hurt you depending on what deck you’re playing against. It’s risky business, but I think it could find its way into many decks since the added twilight can be in the maneuver. Let’s take a look a the BOHD cards.<br />
<br />
Turn of the Tide<br />
Event.<br />
Manuever: Exert Gandalf to discard up to 2 shadow possessions. <br />
The shadow player may discard a minion to prevent this.<br />
Cost:3<br />
<br />
An alternate version of Roll of Thunder. It does require an exertion, but gets rid of an extra possession, making it more efficient. However, it gives the shadow player the choice to toss a minion to prevent it. It requires some planning to pull off effectively, but when used at the right time, it cause serious damage either way. <br />
Arrow Slits (unique)<br />
Condition<br />
Fortification. Plays to your support area. <br />
Manuever: Spot 2 [Rohan] men to discard a possession<br />
or machine. Discard this condition.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Now we’re talking! This is probably the best possession removal card as it is a condition, thus you don’t have to keep it in your hand. You need 2 Rohan down, but I’m sure even non-Rohan decks can fit Eomer and Eowyn in, thus satisfying this card’s requirements…and you don’t need to worry about flooding the pool. The ability to get rid of a machine can be just as valuable, as well. Discarding Weapons of Isengard right after its been loaded is mean. Plus, there is, what, 4 or 5 new machines coming out with BOHD. I’m betting none of them are very nice, either. <br />
<br />
Taurnil, Sharp Eyed Bowman <br />
Elf Companion.<br />
To play, spot an elf. While Taurnil bears a ranged<br />
Weapon, the twilight cost of each shadow possession<br />
is +2 and Taurnil does not add to the fellowship archery<br />
total.<br />
Twilight Cost: 2<br />
Strength: 6<br />
Vitality: 3<br />
<br />
Now, I know he’s not directly possession removal, but indirectly, he is. Most of the time, if your opponent is paying an additional 2 twilight for their possessions, they will more likely end up in the discard pile by your opponent’s choice. Sure, it costs you an archery, but this guy is tech. He is likely to shut down or, at least, greatly hinder possession support.<br />
<br />
Now I’d like to point out a few reasons (or more than a few) to include possession removal. The primary area you might need it is against Nazgul, where discarding the Pale Blade or a Nazgul Sword could save a companion. I don’t see too many Nazgul anymore, but that doesn’t mean it isn’t out there. Nazgul took a hit with the loss of the Ford, but that doesn’t mean you won’t see them. <br />
<br />
In Moria, you will almost always, guaranteed, will see Scimitars, so You’ll see them frequently. Ok, now the discard might not be that big of a deal. After all, they can cycle them back. Taurnil, on the other hand, puts a huge cramp in the twilight adding strategy against Moria. Let’s also not forget the Troll’s accessories or those Moria Axes. It adds up to big twilight and suddenly, your efficient Moria deck isn’t so efficient anymore. <br />
<br />
You’ll most definitely want possession removal against Dunland. Those darn War Clubs (that should have cost 2 to begin with) cost 2 with Taunil or better yet, why not get rid of it before it does you any harm. Hides will definitely take a hit as you can freely discard them, optionally discard 2, or just make them cost 3 apiece. Ouch! Can’t think of any other reasons you’d need it against Dunland, but those 2 cards are good enough.<br />
<br />
Southrons will likely rise up from the ashes in BOHD, so you’ll want to be prepared. The Southron Bow may make an appearance with the new set and there’s nothing like getting rid of a possession your opponent just payed 3 for. Of course, the biggest difference it will make are against those Mumaks. Mumaks are very powerful as they give off large strength bonuses, make their bearer fierce, and adds 2 twilight each time they win or, worse yet, you encounter a War Mumak who adds 5 twilight (Yikes!) each time bearer overwhelms someone. Putting that on a strong Southron, and it could likely add 10 twilight, making a double move almost unthinkable, especially with the loss of 2 guys…and with their new site 6 (that gives 7 twilight, by the way) you may not even have the choice to stay.  Needless to say, you’ll want to stop a monster like this before it stops you. <br />
<br />
Sauron really doesn’t lose anything to possession removal. Orc Scimitars and Vile Blades are the only possessions it has. Few people use Sauron and even fewer use these. Who knows, though. That may change with BOHD so no harm in being prepared.<br />
<br />
While you may see an Ugluk’s Sword or a Broad-bladed sword here and there, Uruk-hai are not very affected by possession removal. Against the new Warg-riders, though, possession removal is, by far, the most brutal. Since the Wargs are expensive already and the riders depend on them to win, making them even more expensive or flat out destroying them will be the bane of this kind of deck. I hate it when decipher decides to screw a new decktype before it even comes out, but BOHD has 3 possession removal cards. I’d pack the removal just for this kind of deck. To be honest, though, this will make too many people paranoid and this decktype may not ever see any play save for the Pre-release. Even then, though, if anyone pulls a Taurnil with their Legolas starter, you’ve basically got it made. He makes the Wargs AND Mumaks +2. He should seriously be banned from pre-release just to make things more fair…(sniff)..ok, I’m done now.<br />
<br />
Anyways, I hope this article enlightened you as to the importance of packing good possession removal in your deck. As I’ve said, it can often be more effective than condition removal…but you make the decision. Is possession discard a good thing?<br />
My answer is yes, but not in Pre-release. You may not agree, but I’m really just voicing my opinion. You think what you want to.<br />
<br />
